T2  - APPLIED SOIL ECOLOGY
AB  - Forest ecosystems are crucial for maintaining global biogeochemical cycles and providing essential ecosystem services. Mixed plantation is increasingly recognized for their potential to enhance biodiversity and soil ecosystem functions compared to monoculture plantations. However, the effect of introducing new tree species into mature monoculture forests on soil multifunctionality remains unclear. Here, we evaluated the impact of mixing new tree species into the monoculture plantation on biodiversity, soil nutrient cycling, water regulation, and soil multifunctionality in the transitional climate zone of central China. This experiment comprised two forest types: a monoculture plantation of Quercus acutissima and a mixed forest incorporating Q. acutissima with Liquidambar formosana. Soil multifunctionality, nitrogen-cycling function, and phosphorus-cycling function significantly increased by 88.9 %, 195.7 %, and 133.2 % after introducing new tree species into the monoculture plantation. Compared to monoculture conditions, mixed plantation significantly decreased understory plant species richness, but increased soil feature index and soil fungal Chao1 index. Soil nitrogen-cycling and phosphorus-cycling functions were positively correlated with the soil fungal Chao1 index and the soil feature index (P < 0.05). Structural equation modeling analysis revealed that soil fungal diversity, rather than understory plant species richness, bacterial diversity, and soil feature index, directly and significantly positively affected soil multifunctionality, with an effect size of 0.824 (P < 0.01). Our findings highlight the potential benefits of incorporating new tree species into mature forest plantations to promote multiple soil functions. This study will provide a mechanistic understanding of the relationship between biodiversity and ecosystem functions after mixing plantation in the subtropical-warm temperate climate transitional forests.
