AB  - A productive soil needs a favorable structure and an efficient nutrient cycling system. Management practices which simultaneously enhance these functions can lead to sustainable land use. The objective of this study was to develop concepts which can be used to link C and N cycling and soil structure formation by using the following model: (1) each organism produces cell structures which are resistant to decomposition. The amount of resistant material contributing to soil structure formation depends upon the size and turnover of the organism; (2) each organism contributes to mineralization of C and N as well as soil structure formation simultaneously, i.e. a portion of C and N during each trophic transfer is used for C and N cycling and a portion is used for soil structure formation. Using the data from the literature and our laboratory, I have: (1) described the structure of organisms; (2) linked the structure of organisms to C and N cycling through soil food webs and to the formation of stabilized soil organic matter; (3) described faunal effects on soil structure; (4) suggested ways to integrate C and N cycling and soil structure formation in current simulation models. The major limitation of current models describing soil ;organic matter dynamics is the lack of description of the formation of aggregates and alteration of porosity through plant root and faunal activity. The availability of fluorescence and micromorphological techniques for in situ visual inspection of soil microenvironments, and three dimensional imaging and modeling techniques, may provide essential data for a sound understanding of the soil matrix effects on microbial growth, microbial-faunal dynamics, fecal material deposition, and formation of macropores in soils and aid in integrating C and N cycling and soil structure formation. This knowledge can be used to develop management systems which enhance soil structure formation, increase the efficiency of C and N cycling, and lead to the development of sustainable land use practices.
