AB  - Microplastics, pervasive pollutants in terrestrial ecosystems, compromise soil health by disrupting microbial diversity and metabolic functions. Indole, a microbial signaling molecule known to regulate quorum sensing and stress adaptation, emerges as a potential mitigator of these disturbances, yet its capacity to counteract microplastic-induced dysbiosis remains uncharacterized. This study investigates how indole reconfigures microbial consortia to enhance ecological resilience under polyethylene (PE) and polystyrene (PS) pollution, employing high-throughput sequencing techniques. The findings revealed that indole significantly enhanced the proliferation of specific bacterial genera, such as Pseudomonas and Bacillus, as well as specific fungal genera, including Trichoderma, Pseudeurotium, and Aspergillus, while increasing their centrality within the microbial network. Compared to the treatment involving only microplastics, the indole treatment notably reduced the impact of microbial community dispersal limitations and enhanced the role of homogeneous selection. A partial least squares discriminant analysis revealed that indole significantly interacted with PE and PS, influencing soil microbial community structure. Moreover, FAPROTAX functional predictions indicated that indole treatment markedly enhanced the metabolic functions of soil microorganisms, including those related to predation or parasitism, the carbon cycle, and the nitrogen cycle, while reducing the relative abundance of potential fungal pathogens. This study indicated the beneficial regulatory effect of indole on the ecological function of microorganisms in soil contaminated by microplastics.
