T2  - FIELD CROPS RESEARCH
AB  - Context: Biofertilizers contain active microorganisms and plant growth-regulating compounds and contribute to the improvement of soil microbial communities and the promotion of crop yields. However, the impact of biofertilizers (containing Bacillus subtilis) on microbial communities, nitrogen cycling, and cotton yields under varying irrigation salinity remains unclear. Objective and methods: This research aimed to examine the impact of biofertilizer (F2) on soil microbial communities, nitrogen cycling processes, and seed cotton yields in cotton fields under fresh water (W1: 0.48 g L-1), brackish water (W2: 3 g L-1), and salt water (W3: 7 g L-1) irrigation, with conventional fertilizer (F1) treatments serving as controls. A two-year field experiment (2021-2022) was conducted in film-mulched drip-irrigated cotton fields. Results and conclusions: Biofertilizers applied in different irrigation waters enhanced microbial abundance and altered both microbial community composition and nitrogen cycling processes. Irrigation water type primarily determined microbial diversity, with reductions observed under brackish and salt conditions. Compared to the W1F1 treatment, the W1F2 treatment significantly increased the expression of ansB (33.82 %) and gdh-K00260 (67.63 %) (N degradation genes), nifK (68.21 %) and nifD (109.84 %) (nitrogen fixation genes), narJ (42.69 %) and narI (21.57 %) (denitrification genes). Similarly, the W2F2 treatment showed elevated levels of ansB (33.93 %) and gdh-K00260 (87.19 %), as well as narJ (37.15 %) and narI (41.22 %), compared to W2F1. Additionally, W2F2 significantly increased nasA (35.09 %), a gene for assimilatory nitrate reduction. Meanwhile, the W1F2 and W2F2 treatments showed significantly higher N agronomic utilization efficiency and seed cotton yield. Notably, the W3F2 treatment showed a significant reduction in amoB-A (48.91 %) and amoA-A (46.55 %) (nitrification genes) compared to the W3F1 treatment. Soil salinity, microbial biomass (carbon and nitrogen), and enzyme activities (urease, invertase, protease, and cellulolytic enzymes) were the primary factors affecting the composition of microbial communities and functional genes of the nitrogen cycle. The partial least squares path analysis indicated that biofertilizers significantly increase cotton productivity by improving soil physicochemical properties and the efficiency of nitrogen fertilizer utilization. The primary factors influencing nitrogen utilization efficiency were identified as key nitrogen cycling functional genes and soil biological properties. Significance: This study offers insights into biofertilizer efficacy under saline water irrigation and provides usefulness for research on other types of biofertilizers.
