TI  - Stimulated soil CO 2 and CH 4 emissions by microplastics: A hierarchical perspective
T2  - SOIL BIOLOGY & BIOCHEMISTRY
AB  - Microplastics have become ubiquitous in soils on a global scale, which may elicit profound deleterious impacts on soil health. However, contradictory case studies have prevented a clear understanding of how microplastics hierarchically impact soil carbon cycling. A meta-analysis was performed to systematically elucidate the effects of microplastics on carbon cycling, particularly in terms of CO 2 and CH 4 emissions. Upon exposure to microplastics, the overall soil CO 2 emissions increased by 54.3%, as were the soil organic carbon (22.6%), dissolved organic carbon (13.3%), and microbial biomass carbon (5.5%). Sufficient carbon substrates supported the replication of functional genes that governed the decomposition of carbon (4.0%; e.g., abfA , sga , and manB , etc.), whereas the gene copies for carbon fixation ( accA and pccA ) were negligibly affected. Moreover, soil enzymatic (e.g., dehydrogenase, fluorescein diacetate hydrolase, and chitinase) activities were also enhanced. Meanwhile, the CO 2 emissions were positively correlated with the gene copy numbers of carbon-decomposing microorganisms. Similarly, the soil CH 4 emissions increased by 9.7%, where the increment of methanogen (41.1%; mcrA ) was slightly higher than that of methanotrophs (37.9%; pmoA , mmoX and mxaF ). Moreover, CH 4 emissions were positively correlated with methanogen gene copies, and the increment of CH 4 emissions was more pronounced in paddy soil (11.3%) than in upland soil. Microplastics with smaller dimensions, round shapes, higher concentrations, and biodegradability leaded to higher soil CO 2 and CH 4 emissions. Meanwhile, the effect sizes of CO 2 and CH 4 emissions decreased over time. These findings revealed that soil carbon cycling was expedited following microplastics exposure, which should be factored into future environmental risk assessments.
