T2  - APPLIED SOIL ECOLOGY
AB  - The prevalence of thaw slumps in permafrost regions has significant influence on soil microbial communities and carbon decomposition, which may be related to the changes in soil pore structure. However, how thaw slumps affect soil microbial communities and its relationship with changes in soil pore structure need further study. In this study, high-throughput sequencing and computed tomography scanning were utilized to analyse the soil microbial communities and pore structure during the development of thaw slumps. The results showed that the changes in the soil pore structure and microbial communities were greater in the subsided area than other area of thaw slumps. The diversity (Shannon index) of soil microbial communities and microbial functions involved in carbon cycling in the 0-10 cm soil increased by 1.41 %-5.09 % and 4.20 %-13.68 % after the development of thaw slumps. The changes in soil microbial communities were related to the soil pore structure during the development of thaw slumps. The pore equivalent diameter decreased by 1.36 %-24.66 % after the development of thaw slumps. The operational taxonomic unit (OTU) and Shannon index of microbial communities exhibited significant negative correlations with the pore equivalent diameter, indicating a negative relationship between microbial diversity and pore size. The microbial functions involved in carbon cycling were also negatively correlated with pore size. In addition, thaw slump enhanced the loss and decomposition of soil organic carbon (SOC), which decreased by 51.50 % (0-10 cm) and 75.62 % (10-20 cm) in the subsided area. Our results highlight that thaw slumps can enhance the microbial diversity and function by regulating soil pore structure, and can exacerbate the carbon decomposition and positive feedback effects of climate warming. These findings provide new perspectives on the dynamics of carbon cycles under global warming.
