AB  - Prokaryotic ureolytic microorganisms play a pivotal role in nitrogen cycling within agricultural ecosystems, driving the conversion of urea into ammonia and participating in various nitrogen-related processes. Despite their importance, there remains a critical gap in our understanding regarding how geographical conditions, soil properties, and biotic interactions, especially under the influence of long-term fertilization, shape the diversity and potential functionality of these microorganisms. In this study, we employed a comprehensive ecological approach to elucidate the factors influencing the biodiversity of prokaryotic ureolytic microorganisms. Our findings revealed that geographical location had the most substantial impact on ureolytic microbial alpha diversity (p < 0.001), explaining nearly half of the observed variation, while fertilization contributed less. However, site-specific responses to fertilization were observed, with increases in Shannon diversity of up to 15 % in some locations and decreases of approximately 10 % in others. Distance-decay analysis showed steeper slopes under fertilization (-4.30 for the Control,-5.43 for NPK (mineral NPK fertilizers), and-6.96 for NPKOM (mineral NPK fertilizers plus organic amendments)), indicating greater heterogeneity in community composition. Co-occurrence network analysis identified five major ecological modules, whose correlations with soil properties (e.g., dissolved organic carbon (DOC), pH and NH4+-N) and functional genes (e.g., amoA, napA, nirS, nifH) in nitrogen cycle varied significantly across fertilization treatments. For instance, under NPK treatment, Module #3 showed a strengthened positive correlation with amoA gene abundance (r = 0.71, p < 0.001), while the negative correlation between Module #4 and DOC became insignificant in NPKOM. These results demonstrate the complex interplay among geography, environmental selection, and biotic interactions in driving ureolytic microbial diversity and functionality under fertilization, offering valuable insights for sustainable soil management practices.
