TI  - Proteomic insights into Methanobactin barkers under polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon stress: Enhanced nutrients uptake and aceticlastic methanogenesis
T2  - JOURNAL OF ENVIRONMENTAL CHEMICAL ENGINEERING
AB  - Anaerobic methanogens play a critical role in global carbon cycling and the production of methane, a valuable clean energy source. However, with industrialization, the accumulation of fluoranthene (Flu) in sediments, soils, and sewage treatment plants has raised concerns about its potential impact on methane production by methanogens. In this paper, the effect of Flu on Methanosarcina barkeri (M. barkeri) was investigated. Methane production at 0.01 and 0.1 mg/L Flu was 1.4-and 1.7-fold higher than that of the control, respectively. The growth of M. barkeri peaked at 0.1 mg/L Flu, reaching 1.4 times that of the control. At this concentration, the physiological characteristics of M. barkeri were enhanced, including cell viability (154 %), total extracellular polymer (1.8-fold), and superoxide dismutase enzyme activity (1.3-fold). Remarkably, TMT-based proteomic analysis revealed that methanogenesis-related metabolic pathways and nutrient uptake of M. barkeri were upregulated under Flu exposure. Specifically, ABC transport proteins involved in the uptake of iron (III), zinc, molybdenum, and vitamin B12 (ModA/C, ZnuA/B/C, and BtuC) were upregulated by 3.1-, 4.5-, and 1.3-fold, respectively, thereby enhancing nutrient availability. In addition, the expression of MtrA/C/D/E/G/H (8.2-fold), FrhA/B/G, and Mcr proteins, which are associated with the groups of methyltransferases, coenzyme F420 hydrogenase, and methane reduction, was significantly increased, promoting the activity of enzymes related to aceticlastic methanogenesis in the presence of Flu. Overall, this study sheds light on the effects of organic contaminants on the global carbon cycle participated by M. barkeri from the molecular biology perspective.
